"Dear Leader Announces.

83
00:04:00,581 --> 00:04:02,786
Wheat Quotas Exceeded
Yet Again."

84
00:04:10,033 --> 00:04:11,770
Ooh, a text.

85
00:04:17,749 --> 00:04:18,884
Returning the shoes?

86
00:04:18,984 --> 00:04:20,822
But then he'll find out...

87
00:04:20,888 --> 00:04:23,426
what really happened.

88
00:04:23,493 --> 00:04:26,165
So hot, no shade.

89
00:04:26,232 --> 00:04:27,602
Maybe this guy will let me sit

90
00:04:27,735 --> 00:04:30,608
under his flat-brimmed
baseball hat?

91
00:04:32,745 --> 00:04:33,981
Homer J. Simpsons.

92
00:04:34,048 --> 00:04:37,354
The line-standing legend himself.

93
00:04:37,421 --> 00:04:39,425
Hey! Mike Wegman!

94
00:04:39,559 --> 00:04:41,864
How's it clangin'?
Where's your food truck?

95
00:04:41,964 --> 00:04:43,968
Somebody pushed it off a bridge,
but don't worry,

96
00:04:44,068 --> 00:04:47,107
I had a good reason, and now
I got an even better business.

97
00:04:47,174 --> 00:04:49,211
Selling those
limited-edition sneakers.

98
00:04:49,345 --> 00:04:50,748
You want a pair?

99
00:04:50,848 --> 00:04:52,451
Oh, my God,
my kid's begging for these.

100
00:04:52,519 --> 00:04:53,954
How much do I owe you?

101
00:04:54,054 --> 00:04:55,658
You owe me?

102
00:04:55,725 --> 00:04:58,329
How much do the pilgrims
owe the Statue of Liberty?

103
00:04:58,396 --> 00:05:00,535
How much does hot dog
owe a mustard?

104
00:05:00,601 --> 00:05:03,106
For you, these are on the house.

105
00:05:03,206 --> 00:05:04,943
Oh, thank you so much.

106
00:05:05,010 --> 00:05:07,949
Don't worry about it, these
aren't real Slipremes anyway.

107
00:05:08,016 --> 00:05:09,553
What? They're fake?

108
00:05:09,619 --> 00:05:12,224
Oh, but I promised
my son the real ones.

109
00:05:12,257 --> 00:05:14,696
Who, Bart, huh?
That bed-wetting nobody?

110
00:05:14,763 --> 00:05:17,134
He won't be able
to tell the difference.

111
00:05:17,201 --> 00:05:19,305
Kids today aren't
like you and me.

112
00:05:19,371 --> 00:05:21,910
They're dumb
because of phones or whatever.

113
00:05:22,010 --> 00:05:25,985
Hmm, and I do like
getting away with things.

114
00:05:26,018 --> 00:05:27,555
That's winner talk there.

115
00:05:27,655 --> 00:05:30,327
Hey, which of you freak shows
wants to do business?

116
00:05:30,393 --> 00:05:32,632
I like your dumb hat.

117
00:05:39,813 --> 00:05:42,417
I got to stop Bart from
returning those fake sneakers.

118
00:05:42,484 --> 00:05:44,255
"No no no no no!"

119
00:05:44,321 --> 00:05:46,860
Thanks, Dad, it is on.

120
00:05:46,927 --> 00:05:48,607
Bart Simpson here,
about to clown some fools

121
00:05:48,631 --> 00:05:50,935
who sold me
some crappy sneakers.

122
00:05:51,035 --> 00:05:53,908
These shoes are trash.
I want my money back.

123
00:05:53,974 --> 00:05:56,747
Uh, real Caliphate Twos
aren't made from garbage.

124
00:05:56,813 --> 00:06:00,053
They're vegan leather made
from upcycled recycling bins.

125
00:06:00,120 --> 00:06:01,857
Wait, what?

126
00:06:01,924 --> 00:06:03,393
These are fakes.

127
00:06:03,493 --> 00:06:06,232
You're trying to return
bootleg sneakers.

128
00:06:06,299 --> 00:06:08,871
You can't record me...
I'm recording you.

129
00:06:08,938 --> 00:06:10,508
What up, Shauna Nation?

130
00:06:10,575 --> 00:06:12,545
As always, I'm Shauna.

131
00:06:12,645 --> 00:06:15,483
Look at this idiot,
trying to return a knock-off.

132
00:06:15,551 --> 00:06:18,891
Link in my bio
to win free edible eyeshadow.

133
00:06:18,991 --> 00:06:20,227
They're not fake.

134
00:06:22,599 --> 00:06:25,805
My Dad waited in line for these
shoes and spent a lot of money.

135
00:06:25,938 --> 00:06:28,376
And Homer Simpson
would never lie to his son

136
00:06:28,409 --> 00:06:31,148
just to get out
of standing in li...

137
00:06:31,215 --> 00:06:33,419
Oh, my God,
he bought me fake shoes.

138
00:06:33,486 --> 00:06:35,190
Bart, don't return the shoes!

139
00:06:35,257 --> 00:06:36,192
This is just a dream.

140
00:06:36,259 --> 00:06:38,129
Wake up, Bart. Wake up.

141
00:06:38,196 --> 00:06:39,733
How could you?

142
00:06:39,799 --> 00:06:41,102
I will never be more embarrassed

143
00:06:41,168 --> 00:06:43,473
than I am right now.

144
00:06:45,477 --> 00:06:48,049
We have underpants.

145
00:06:48,149 --> 00:06:50,588
You've ruined me!

146
00:06:50,688 --> 00:06:52,457
Please like and subscribe.

147
00:06:56,900 --> 00:06:59,506
Stupid Homer.
Turned me into a GIF.

148
00:07:00,307 --> 00:07:02,512
Oh, man.

149
00:07:03,714 --> 00:07:06,352
You're even a dance.
It's called

150
00:07:06,452 --> 00:07:08,222
the "Pants Kid Shimmy."

151
00:07:08,289 --> 00:07:10,293
It's everywhere!

152
00:07:19,211 --> 00:07:21,415
So fun!

153
00:07:21,482 --> 00:07:23,654
Son, I got you
this apology card.

154
00:07:23,754 --> 00:07:26,025
The duck, you know,
on the front, he thinks

155
00:07:26,125 --> 00:07:29,331
what I did was "quackers,"
and maybe he's right.

156
00:07:29,465 --> 00:07:31,035
Don't ever talk to me again!

157
00:07:31,135 --> 00:07:33,015
What was I thinking, trusting
you to help me look cool?

158
00:07:33,039 --> 00:07:35,377
You're the least cool person
who ever lived.

159
00:07:35,477 --> 00:07:37,314
But that includes Urkel.

160
00:07:37,381 --> 00:07:39,418
You're bald.
You own a bowling ball.

161
00:07:39,519 --> 00:07:41,422
You own truck nuts but no truck.

162
00:07:41,523 --> 00:07:44,061
You've seen Tim Allen's standup
multiple times.

163
00:07:44,128 --> 00:07:45,631
You still have a CD tower.

164
00:07:45,731 --> 00:07:47,000
And each one your three kids

165
00:07:47,067 --> 00:07:48,667
is embarrassed by you
in a different way.

166
00:07:50,574 --> 00:07:52,377
You were born uncool

167
00:07:52,444 --> 00:07:54,348
and every day for four decades,

168
00:07:54,415 --> 00:07:56,620
you've gotten less cool.

169
00:07:58,489 --> 00:08:00,861
I know I'm not exactly
Stefan Urquelle,

170
00:08:00,928 --> 00:08:04,001
but didn't you ever think
your old man was a little cool?

171
00:08:04,068 --> 00:08:06,573
Never. Not one bit.

172
00:08:11,683 --> 00:08:14,088
I'm sorry to bother you.
I'm looking for Bart Simpson.

173
00:08:14,154 --> 00:08:15,423
Orion Hughes!

174
00:08:15,490 --> 00:08:17,995
I found your critically-maligned
book of poetry

175
00:08:18,096 --> 00:08:20,233
to be weirdly moving.

176
00:08:20,300 --> 00:08:23,540
Yeah, I thought poetry
would be hard, but it wasn't.

177
00:08:23,574 --> 00:08:25,644
I know you. You're the voice

178
00:08:25,745 --> 00:08:27,515
of the urban squid
from the live-action.

179
00:08:27,615 --> 00:08:29,284
Finding Nemo.

180
00:08:30,353 --> 00:08:32,257
Bart, I wanted to apologize

181
00:08:32,324 --> 00:08:34,294
for the way
my employees shamed you.

182
00:08:34,361 --> 00:08:35,664
You heard about that?

183
00:08:35,798 --> 00:08:38,236
Ooh, I saw that dance

184
00:08:38,302 --> 00:08:40,741
on Ellen today.

185
00:08:41,977 --> 00:08:43,547
You didn't know
the shoes were fake.

186
00:08:43,680 --> 00:08:45,200
To make up
for your global humiliation,

187
00:08:45,250 --> 00:08:47,889
I brought your family
some free Slipreme skatewear.

188
00:08:52,130 --> 00:08:54,636
Whoa, new skateboards!

189
00:08:57,842 --> 00:09:00,146
Grab a board,
show me what you got.

190
00:09:00,246 --> 00:09:02,084
Uh, I'd love to, of course.

191
00:09:02,150 --> 00:09:04,889
But the thing is,
I have a deal with Slim Jim.

192
00:09:04,956 --> 00:09:08,697
I can't skate unless I'm holding
a Dr. Pepper Salami Twister.

193
00:09:08,797 --> 00:09:10,500
Come on,
just ollie off the curb.

194
00:09:10,568 --> 00:09:12,572
Ollie?
Oh, yeah, that's the move

195
00:09:12,672 --> 00:09:14,475
where you throw it, right?

196
00:09:14,576 --> 00:09:16,278
Ollie!

197
00:09:16,378 --> 00:09:20,353
You own a skatewear company
and you don't know how to skate?

198
00:09:22,525 --> 00:09:23,994
Please don't tell anyone.

199
00:09:24,094 --> 00:09:25,698
Hey, dude, no worries.

200
00:09:25,765 --> 00:09:27,869
You know what?
I can teach you to skate.

201
00:09:27,935 --> 00:09:29,873
But what if I'm not
instantly amazing at it?

202
00:09:29,939 --> 00:09:32,177
I've heard that can happen.

203
00:09:32,979 --> 00:09:35,183
Okay, feet on the board,
bend your knees,

204
00:09:35,250 --> 00:09:36,653
find your center...

205
00:09:36,753 --> 00:09:38,891
See? You're doing it!

206
00:09:38,991 --> 00:09:40,828
I'm doing it. I-I'm authentic.

207
00:09:40,895 --> 00:09:43,099
No one's ever been this real.

208
00:09:43,199 --> 00:09:45,136
Don't fall down!

209
00:09:45,203 --> 00:09:46,840
What's "falling down"?

210
00:09:51,750 --> 00:09:53,520
That's-that's my blood.

211
00:09:53,554 --> 00:09:55,323
I've never seen it before.

212
00:09:55,390 --> 00:09:57,394
So cool. Let's go again.

213
00:09:59,766 --> 00:10:02,638
Can you pass the guacamole,
#GuacAttack?

214
00:10:04,609 --> 00:10:06,713
You're hashtagging a lot lately.

215
00:10:06,780 --> 00:10:09,418
So Bart called you uncool,
big deal.

216
00:10:09,485 --> 00:10:11,523
Chasing after coolness
is futile,

217
00:10:11,656 --> 00:10:13,326
because the definition
is both arbitrary

218
00:10:13,392 --> 00:10:15,230
and constantly changing.

219
00:10:15,330 --> 00:10:17,367
Mm, still want to be it.

220
00:10:19,539 --> 00:10:21,843
With hard shell tacos,
you've got to bite them

221
00:10:21,910 --> 00:10:24,148
from the bottom, like this.

222
00:10:26,118 --> 00:10:27,354
Why?!

223
00:10:27,420 --> 00:10:30,360
Why do I keep buying
hard shells?

224
00:10:30,426 --> 00:10:32,430
I hate them!

225
00:10:32,497 --> 00:10:34,434
Uh, I'm going to Moe's.

226
00:10:34,502 --> 00:10:36,773
At least put on a clean shirt.

227
00:10:44,856 --> 00:10:45,758
Homer.

228
00:10:45,825 --> 00:10:47,360
Check it out... I'm selling

229
00:10:47,427 --> 00:10:49,231
premium Wagyu-style steaks.

230
00:10:49,298 --> 00:10:51,168
The 72-month subscription plan...

231
00:10:51,235 --> 00:10:53,640
It comes with a genuine
landline phone.

232
00:10:53,707 --> 00:10:56,312
I'm too depressed to figure out
what you're saying.

233
00:10:58,416 --> 00:11:00,153
That's a Slipreme hoodie.

234
00:11:00,253 --> 00:11:03,760
And that ain't even a knock-off
like these donkey steaks.

235
00:11:04,562 --> 00:11:05,898
I got to post this.

236
00:11:05,965 --> 00:11:08,670
Whoa, someone posted
a picture of me,

237
00:11:08,770 --> 00:11:11,308
and it it's not
for falling down an escalator

238
00:11:11,408 --> 00:11:13,279
or yelling at a parking meter.

239
00:11:13,346 --> 00:11:14,883
Which means I must be...

240
00:11:14,983 --> 00:11:17,822
Cool. Yes, you are now cool.

241
00:11:17,955 --> 00:11:19,926
I've been liked.

242
00:11:19,993 --> 00:11:21,863
Someone enjoyed looking at me.

243
00:11:21,963 --> 00:11:24,903
Finally, I know
how it feels to be stylish.

244
00:11:25,003 --> 00:11:26,706
To be loved for my appearance

245
00:11:26,840 --> 00:11:28,744
instead of judged
for my actions.

246
00:11:28,844 --> 00:11:31,315
This is why people

247
00:11:31,415 --> 00:11:33,252
own more than one outfit.

248
00:11:33,319 --> 00:11:36,091
Thank you, Mike Wegman!

249
00:11:37,728 --> 00:11:40,500
540 flip straight onto your ear.

250
00:11:42,003 --> 00:11:43,005
Legendary!

251
00:11:43,105 --> 00:11:44,909
Am I still slurring my's words?

252
00:11:44,976 --> 00:11:47,247
Uh, it's-it's barely noticeable.

253
00:11:47,314 --> 00:11:49,686
Having a movie star dad,
I don't really get

254
00:11:49,752 --> 00:11:51,255
to hang out with regular kids.

255
00:11:51,322 --> 00:11:53,068
With you I can relax,
you know, without having

256
00:11:53,092 --> 00:11:55,396
to redefine our generation's
notion of relaxation.

257
00:11:55,496 --> 00:11:57,000
I guess I envy you.

258
00:11:57,067 --> 00:11:59,672
Isn't that something
rich people say to poor people

259
00:11:59,739 --> 00:12:02,277
so that they feel less guilty
about being rich?

260
00:12:02,344 --> 00:12:05,216
Yes, but for the first time,
I mean it.

261
00:12:05,283 --> 00:12:07,722
You helped me bleed.
Maybe I can help you.

262
00:12:07,822 --> 00:12:10,093
What if we design
a new sneaker together?

263
00:12:10,159 --> 00:12:12,163
A sneaker that
all my friends will buy?

264
00:12:12,264 --> 00:12:15,036
No, a sneaker that all
your friends will want to buy,

265
00:12:15,136 --> 00:12:18,009
but can't, because we won't
make enough of them.

266
00:12:18,109 --> 00:12:20,280
That's even better.

267
00:12:23,352 --> 00:12:24,923
What the hell are you wearing?

268
00:12:25,023 --> 00:12:27,862
I know what it is...
A hobo was murdered at a rave,

269
00:12:27,929 --> 00:12:30,901
and Homer's going undercover
to find the killer.

270
00:12:31,001 --> 00:12:33,239
Nah, nah, nah,
he drove a motorcycle

271
00:12:33,339 --> 00:12:36,546
through the clothesline
of a bi-curious farmer.

272
00:12:36,613 --> 00:12:38,984
I was once like you.

273
00:12:39,084 --> 00:12:41,623
Wearing clothes
I bought at the gas station

274
00:12:41,690 --> 00:12:43,392
or found at the beach.

275
00:12:43,459 --> 00:12:46,332
But I've learned something...
When you wear crazy clothes

276
00:12:46,398 --> 00:12:49,471
you don't understand,
you're not you anymore.

277
00:12:49,539 --> 00:12:51,643
You're someone better.

278
00:12:51,743 --> 00:12:53,547
Oh, my God.

279
00:12:53,647 --> 00:12:55,851
I'm beautiful.

280
00:13:03,567 --> 00:13:04,636
Hey.

281
00:13:04,702 --> 00:13:07,273
Well, look at me...
I'm a real Hep Cat.

282
00:13:07,374 --> 00:13:11,448
And not just because
I got Hep C, A and T.

283
00:13:11,516 --> 00:13:13,386
Which, I-I do got those.

284
00:13:13,486 --> 00:13:17,093
We must tell all middle-aged men
that they need not grow old.

285
00:13:17,160 --> 00:13:19,899
Where do the graying masses
gather to worship?

286
00:13:34,361 --> 00:13:36,198
Bart, together
we'll design a sneaker

287
00:13:36,265 --> 00:13:39,237
that'll change
sneaker culture forever.

288
00:13:39,338 --> 00:13:41,141
Which, in this business,
is one week.

289
00:14:05,456 --> 00:14:07,595
The Bartman One.

290
00:14:07,695 --> 00:14:10,266
My life has mattered.

291
00:14:10,366 --> 00:14:13,172
Yeah, and it comes
with a sticker in the box.

292
00:14:13,272 --> 00:14:15,343
The release party
is Saturday night.

293
00:14:15,443 --> 00:14:17,047
It's gonna be perfect.

294
00:14:17,113 --> 00:14:19,317
The right music,
the right influencers,

295
00:14:19,418 --> 00:14:21,422
and every single person there
will be young,

296
00:14:21,488 --> 00:14:23,359
cool and beautiful.

297
00:14:23,459 --> 00:14:26,165
Excuse me,
do you have this in a large?

298
00:14:26,265 --> 00:14:28,035
You're buying that for yourself?

299
00:14:28,135 --> 00:14:30,339
But old people don't
know about my clothes.

300
00:14:30,473 --> 00:14:32,143
Unless...

301
00:14:32,210 --> 00:14:33,780
Oh, no.

302
00:14:33,847 --> 00:14:34,882
They're here.

303
00:14:34,982 --> 00:14:36,820
The middle-aged.

304
00:14:36,886 --> 00:14:38,523
The uncool!

305
00:14:46,573 --> 00:14:47,875
This is a nightmare.

306
00:14:47,975 --> 00:14:50,714
My brand's been
discovered by dads.

307
00:14:50,781 --> 00:14:53,252
I'm wearing this to da club.

308
00:14:53,319 --> 00:14:54,956
Da bridge club.

309
00:14:55,056 --> 00:14:56,793
It's like Ed Hardy
all over again.

310
00:14:56,860 --> 00:14:58,964
Who the heck is Ed Hardy?

311
00:14:59,030 --> 00:15:02,070
Ed Hardy was
a California tattoo artist

312
00:15:02,137 --> 00:15:04,107
whose unique designs
were the epitome of cool.

313
00:15:04,174 --> 00:15:05,844
But then, one terrible day,

314
00:15:05,944 --> 00:15:08,449
a newly-divorced dad
wanted to seem younger

315
00:15:08,550 --> 00:15:09,819
on his dating profile.

316
00:15:09,886 --> 00:15:11,623
He bought
a sleeveless tee in XXL

317
00:15:11,689 --> 00:15:13,359
and then posted the picture.

318
00:15:13,426 --> 00:15:15,496
Young people saw
old people wearing the brand,

319
00:15:15,564 --> 00:15:17,902
and weeks later,
a $700 million empire

320
00:15:17,968 --> 00:15:19,572
was sold for scrap.

321
00:15:20,874 --> 00:15:22,812
Stupid old losers.

322
00:15:22,912 --> 00:15:25,249
Slipreme's gonna die.
What do I do?!

323
00:15:25,316 --> 00:15:27,287
I don't know,
but we can think of something.

324
00:15:27,353 --> 00:15:30,259
We're two of the coolest kids
in the world, right?

325
00:15:30,326 --> 00:15:32,565
So cool. You've even
got your own sneaker.

326
00:15:32,665 --> 00:15:34,134
That's cool, isn't it?

327
00:15:34,234 --> 00:15:36,038
I don't even know anymore.

328
00:15:36,105 --> 00:15:38,209
Hey, Bart, thank your old man

329
00:15:38,309 --> 00:15:41,048
for introducing me
to the look of the street.

330
00:15:41,081 --> 00:15:44,922
Wait, Homer's the reason you're
all wearing these clothes?

331
00:15:44,989 --> 00:15:46,659
You know it.

332
00:15:46,726 --> 00:15:48,663
If my dad started this,

333
00:15:48,730 --> 00:15:50,366
maybe he can stop it.

334
00:15:50,433 --> 00:15:52,905
Yes, can I pay
for this paisley tracksuit

335
00:15:52,972 --> 00:15:55,209
with airline miles?

336
00:15:57,581 --> 00:15:59,619
Ooh. Ee. Ooh.

337
00:15:59,685 --> 00:16:01,856
Drop the selfie stick now.

338
00:16:01,923 --> 00:16:03,693
What about my Lookbook?

339
00:16:04,962 --> 00:16:06,566
Stop dressing
your zombie friends up

340
00:16:06,633 --> 00:16:07,935
in the clothes of the living.

341
00:16:08,035 --> 00:16:10,439
Never!
Before I discovered streetwear,

342
00:16:10,507 --> 00:16:12,945
people... like my son...

343
00:16:13,012 --> 00:16:15,483
Treated me
like a dried-up old husk.

344
00:16:15,551 --> 00:16:17,988
Well, you know what I am now?
A wet husk.

345
00:16:18,055 --> 00:16:21,161
Full of juicy corn.
Mmm, corn, Bart.

346
00:16:21,261 --> 00:16:24,635
You hear me? Mmm, corn.

347
00:16:24,702 --> 00:16:27,006
Orion and I made
something amazing together,

348
00:16:27,040 --> 00:16:28,844
and you're ruining it.

349
00:16:28,910 --> 00:16:30,647
Too bad.

350
00:16:30,714 --> 00:16:34,287
'Cause we're all going
to your sneaker release party.

351
00:16:35,323 --> 00:16:37,160
Just because they RSVP'd,

352
00:16:37,293 --> 00:16:39,464
doesn't mean
they're actually coming.

353
00:16:39,532 --> 00:16:41,569
Wrong. My generation

354
00:16:41,669 --> 00:16:43,740
shows up to things.

355
00:16:48,048 --> 00:16:51,388
This is horrible. My Dad
told all his loser friends

356
00:16:51,488 --> 00:16:53,025
about this party.

357
00:16:53,092 --> 00:16:55,931
No, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no, no.

358
00:16:56,031 --> 00:16:57,935
Aah! It's my dad.

359
00:16:58,002 --> 00:16:59,772
Act like everything's fine.

360
00:16:59,872 --> 00:17:01,809
Son, I've never seen your aura

361
00:17:01,876 --> 00:17:03,947
looking less indigo.
Are you okay?

362
00:17:04,014 --> 00:17:06,084
Nothing-nothing's wrong.
I'm crushing it.

363
00:17:06,184 --> 00:17:08,990
I got this on lock. On lock.

364
00:17:09,057 --> 00:17:10,994
Your words have convinced me.

365
00:17:11,061 --> 00:17:13,065
The washed-up dads
are gonna be here soon.

366
00:17:13,165 --> 00:17:15,269
- I read about it in.
- The Old... Timers Gazette:

367
00:17:15,369 --> 00:17:16,873
Facebook.

368
00:17:16,906 --> 00:17:18,175
I can't handle this.

369
00:17:18,275 --> 00:17:20,781
And my therapist
is pitching his sitcom today.

370
00:17:20,814 --> 00:17:23,520
Which I'm producing.

371
00:17:24,487 --> 00:17:27,060
You said if I ever needed you,
you'd come.

372
00:17:27,193 --> 00:17:29,932
No matter what.
This is that call.

373
00:17:30,032 --> 00:17:33,707
Okie-dokie. Want me to grab you
some mini carrots and hummus?

374
00:17:33,807 --> 00:17:35,510
Yes.

375
00:17:38,115 --> 00:17:39,619
Listen up, people.

376
00:17:39,719 --> 00:17:42,056
For the first time
in your horrible lives,

377
00:17:42,123 --> 00:17:44,996
you are not the lamest losers
in the world.

378
00:17:47,133 --> 00:17:49,404
So if any young person
asks you what you do,

379
00:17:49,505 --> 00:17:53,345
say, "Virtual marketing
for a CBD massage oil startup."

380
00:17:53,445 --> 00:17:56,653
Now everyone take
two precautionary Advil

381
00:17:56,719 --> 00:17:58,757
and let's live forever!

382
00:17:59,926 --> 00:18:01,261
Homer, stop it!

383
00:18:01,328 --> 00:18:04,200
Dads, halt. Let my shorty speak.

384
00:18:04,267 --> 00:18:07,006
Homer, this isn't who you are.

385
00:18:07,106 --> 00:18:09,979
You're right...
It's better than who I am.

386
00:18:10,046 --> 00:18:12,785
This is the man I married.

387
00:18:12,851 --> 00:18:15,022
You call all deli meats baloney.

388
00:18:15,089 --> 00:18:16,826
You carry clippers
on your key chain

389
00:18:16,893 --> 00:18:19,832
so you can cut your nails
in line at the post office.

390
00:18:19,899 --> 00:18:22,671
You spent your stimulus check
on funny bumper stickers

391
00:18:22,738 --> 00:18:25,209
about what you spent your
stimulus check on.

392
00:18:25,276 --> 00:18:27,280
And since the day
I first saw you

393
00:18:27,380 --> 00:18:29,417
moonwalk out of an Arby's,

394
00:18:29,552 --> 00:18:32,056
you've been comfortable
in your own skin.

395
00:18:32,123 --> 00:18:34,327
Until now.

396
00:18:35,697 --> 00:18:38,102
I look...

397
00:18:38,168 --> 00:18:40,072
ridiculous!

398
00:18:40,139 --> 00:18:42,778
I shouldn't be
at a sneaker release party.

399
00:18:42,845 --> 00:18:44,047
I should be at home.

400
00:18:44,147 --> 00:18:47,554
Making microwave popcorn.

401
00:18:47,655 --> 00:18:50,226
My favorite show.

402
00:18:50,326 --> 00:18:52,564
We don't belong here.

403
00:18:52,665 --> 00:18:54,167
Men our age

404
00:18:54,234 --> 00:18:56,673
belong in here.

405
00:18:57,975 --> 00:19:00,413
The Museum of Aviation History.

406
00:19:05,222 --> 00:19:07,828
The cross section
of a real B-52.

407
00:19:07,895 --> 00:19:11,736
An IMAX movie about
the golden age of ballooning.

408
00:19:11,803 --> 00:19:15,476
Audio tour by Gary Sinise.

409
00:19:15,544 --> 00:19:18,415
It worked.
They took the dad-bait.

410
00:19:20,019 --> 00:19:21,355
Dad.

411
00:19:21,455 --> 00:19:24,829
You did something no old person
is remotely capable of.

412
00:19:24,862 --> 00:19:26,933
You changed your mind.

413
00:19:27,033 --> 00:19:29,037
I'm sorry
I almost ruined everything

414
00:19:29,104 --> 00:19:31,041
for you and your friend.

415
00:19:31,141 --> 00:19:33,212
I have no business
wearing skatewear.

416
00:19:33,278 --> 00:19:35,483
I don't even like to ice skate.

417
00:19:37,521 --> 00:19:40,192
I never got a pair of my own
shoes, and now they're sold out.

418
00:19:40,259 --> 00:19:43,767
Yo, style freaks.
I got counterfeit Bart Ones.

419
00:19:43,833 --> 00:19:45,469
Genuine knockoffs.

420
00:19:45,537 --> 00:19:47,306
Your dumb friends
can't tell the difference

421
00:19:47,373 --> 00:19:49,845
unless you wear 'em
or you look at 'em close.

422
00:19:55,524 --> 00:19:59,064
Thanks, Dad. Sometimes
you are a little bit cool.

423
00:19:59,130 --> 00:20:01,969
Buy you a chicken sandwich?

424
00:20:21,374 --> 00:20:23,178
Dad, tonight was a close call.

425
00:20:23,245 --> 00:20:24,791
This party was almost not
a cultural gamechanger.

426
00:20:24,815 --> 00:20:26,986
I hope you're not
disappointed in me.

427
00:20:27,053 --> 00:20:28,990
Oh, you can never let me down,

428
00:20:29,090 --> 00:20:31,128
because I know
exactly how you feel.

429
00:20:31,194 --> 00:20:32,865
Because you're me.

430
00:20:32,965 --> 00:20:34,668
No, Dad. I'm not you.

431
00:20:34,769 --> 00:20:36,204
And I'll never be you.

432
00:20:36,271 --> 00:20:38,610
You're not
hearing what I'm saying.

433
00:20:38,710 --> 00:20:39,979
You're me.

434
00:20:40,012 --> 00:20:42,417
A clone of me.
Like this.

435
00:20:43,720 --> 00:20:46,692
You were created on the set
of Duplicate Cop One,

436
00:20:46,759 --> 00:20:49,565
which we filmed
in a real cloning lab.

437
00:20:52,538 --> 00:20:53,907
I knew I could never
love a child

438
00:20:54,007 --> 00:20:57,648
as much as I love myself,
so I made another me:

439
00:20:57,714 --> 00:20:58,516
You.

440
00:20:58,583 --> 00:21:01,421
But how... But I... But...
What?

441
00:21:01,455 --> 00:21:03,693
Didn't you ever wonder
why you don't have a mother?

442
00:21:03,827 --> 00:21:06,833
- Kind of.
- Orion, our cosmic connection

443
00:21:06,899 --> 00:21:08,168
is infinitely deeper

444
00:21:08,268 --> 00:21:10,272
than what a "father"
feels for a "son."

445
00:21:10,372 --> 00:21:12,376
I love you, me.

446
00:21:12,443 --> 00:21:15,149
I love you, too... me.

